# Requirements Document: AI-Powered Appraisal System

## 1. Functional Requirements

### Data Integration & Aggregation
1. The system SHALL integrate with Jira/Project Management tools to ingest ticket completion rates, story points delivered, and sprint velocity.
2. The system SHALL ingest quality metrics including bugs created vs. bugs fixed and code review participation rates.
3. The system SHALL integrate with Git/Version Control systems to analyze commit frequency and patterns.
4. The system SHALL assess code review quality based on comment substance and knowledge sharing indicators.
5. The system SHALL track Pull Request approval rates and collaboration metrics.
6. The system SHALL aggregate peer feedback and 360-degree review data.
7. The system SHALL ingest incident post-mortem reports and contributions.
8. The system SHALL track recognition and kudos from team members.
9. The system SHALL integrate with Learning & Development platforms to track completed courses, certifications, and internal knowledge sharing (documentation, tech talks).
10. The system SHALL track mentorship activities.
11. The system SHALL allow ingestion of employee-submitted self-assessments, achievements, reflections, and goal progress (OKRs/KPIs).
12. The system SHALL ingest historical appraisal data including previous ratings, improvement areas, and career progression patterns.

### AI/NLP Capabilities
13. The system SHALL perform weighted scoring across different data sources for intelligent aggregation.
14. The system SHALL apply contextual understanding (e.g., normalizing activity during on-call rotations).
15. The system SHALL perform anomaly detection for sudden changes in performance patterns.
16. The system SHALL convert technical metrics into readable performance narratives via Natural Language Generation.
17. The system SHALL generate identified strengths, areas for improvement, and development suggestions.
18. The system SHALL tailor language tone to the organizational culture.
19. The system SHALL flag potential recency bias (overweighting recent work vs. full period).
20. The system SHALL identify language patterns suggesting gender or cultural bias.
21. The system SHALL normalize data based on team size, project complexity, and role expectations.
22. The system SHALL identify hidden contributions (glue work, mentorship, knowledge sharing).
23. The system SHALL benchmark employee performance against role-level expectations.
24. The system SHALL surface growth trajectory and potential indicators.

### Manager Interface Features
25. The system SHALL provide a unified dashboard showing a single view of all aggregated employee data.
26. The system SHALL generate an AI draft appraisal with cited data sources.
27. The system SHALL allow managers to edit, add context, and override AI suggestions.
28. The system SHALL show employees which specific data points contributed to their review (Transparency Controls).
29. The system SHALL maintain a log (audit trail) of manager edits vs. AI recommendations.
30. The system SHALL support Calibration by comparing ratings across a team.
31. The system SHALL flag outlier ratings for manager/HR review.
32. The system SHALL suggest rating adjustments to improve fairness.

### Employee Experience (Self-Service)
33. The system SHALL allow employees to add contextual notes to their metrics (e.g., explaining low commit activity due to on-call duty).
34. The system SHALL allow employees to highlight non-technical contributions (e.g., mentorship, documentation).
35. The system SHALL allow employees to upload supporting artifacts (presentations, customer feedback, design docs).
36. The system SHALL provide real-time visibility into performance progress tracking throughout the review period.
37. The system SHALL provide early warnings to employees if performance metrics are trending downward.
38. The system SHALL provide AI-powered improvement suggestions (e.g., workshop recommendations).

### HR & Calibration Features
39. The system SHALL track overall appraisal cycle progress (e.g., completion rate, days in cycle).
40. The system SHALL flag calibration issues automatically (e.g., manager leniency, low consistency, gender bias patterns, recency bias).
41. The system SHALL provide an organization rating distribution chart.
42. The system SHALL provide a manager team comparison graph.
43. The system SHALL show manager consistency analysis (team size, avg rating, standard deviation, outliers, status).

## 2. Non-Functional Requirements (High Level)

44. **Efficiency**: The system SHALL reduce manager appraisal prep time from 3-4 hours to 20-30 minutes per employee.
45. **Efficiency**: The system SHALL reduce the overall HR appraisal cycle from 6 weeks to 2 weeks.
46. **Performance**: The system SHALL support appraisal cycles with thousands of concurrent users.
47. **Availability**: The system SHALL ensure high availability during peak "appraisal season" (e.g., end of quarter/cycle).
48. **Security**: The system MUST comply with GDPR and SOC2 standards for employee data protection.
49. **Auditability**: The system MUST maintain a complete audit trail of AI recommendations, manager overrides, and data sources used.
50. **Explainability**: The AI model SHALL provide explainability for its scoring and narrative generation.

## 3. External Integrations

51. **Jira** (Project/Ticket Management)
52. **Git** (Version Control - e.g., GitHub, GitLab, Bitbucket)
53. **Feedback Systems** (e.g., Officevibe, Lattice, or custom 360-tools)
54. **Learning & Development Platforms** (e.g., LinkedIn Learning, Udemy, internal LMS)
55. **HRIS** (Potential future integration for employee baseline data)

## 4. User Roles and Permissions

56. **Employee (Individual Contributor)**
    - Permissions: View own dashboard, add context to own metrics, upload own artifacts, view own performance trend, view AI suggestions for self-improvement.
57. **Engineering Manager**
    - Permissions: View aggregated data for direct reports, generate/edit/override AI appraisal drafts, view team calibration data, view audit trail of their own edits.
58. **HR Business Partner**
    - Permissions: Oversee whole organization/division appraisal process, view calibration dashboards for all managers, flag compliance issues, access audit logs, run compliance reports.
59. **Senior Leader / Director**
    - Permissions: View second-level appraisals, view promotion recommendations, view high-level talent distribution and flight risk indicators.

## 5. Data Sensitivity Classification

60. **Public Data** (Non-sensitive)
    - General system documentation, UI text labels (non-personal), marketing descriptions of the tool.
61. **Confidential Data** (Internal use only)
    - Aggregated team velocity metrics (non-attributed), anonymized calibration statistics (e.g., "30% of teams show leniency bias").
    - System performance metrics.
62. **PII (Personally Identifiable Information) / Sensitive**
    - Employee names, IDs, email addresses.
    - Individual performance ratings and trajectories.
    - Peer feedback text (360 reviews).
    - Self-assessment narratives.
    - Manager override notes and qualitative comments.
    - Audit trail linking specific actions to specific users (managers or HR).
    - Compensation-related data (inferred from promotion decisions).
